need to know a couple of things
to tell you everything

00:47:11.460 --> 00:47:16.240
about this mixture.

00:47:16.240 --> 00:47:22.750
And this example here is a
specific example of something

00:47:22.750 --> 00:47:24.370
called the Gibbs phase rule.

00:47:24.370 --> 00:47:27.580
Which you've seen before.

00:47:27.580 --> 00:47:28.980
In this diagram.

00:47:28.980 --> 00:47:33.880
In this diagram that
we wrote here.

00:47:33.880 --> 00:47:38.780
Where, let me write down what
the Gibbs phase rule is first.

00:47:38.780 --> 00:47:41.410
The Gibbs phase rule tells you
the number of independent

00:47:41.410 --> 00:47:43.710
variables given a number
of constraints.

00:47:43.710 --> 00:47:56.930
So, it tells you that the number
of degrees of freedom,

00:47:56.930 --> 00:47:59.290
the number of independent
variables in a mixture, in a

00:47:59.290 --> 00:48:03.140
complicated system like this,
is equal to C, which is the

00:48:03.140 --> 00:48:05.050
number of components.

00:48:05.050 --> 00:48:09.470
So in this case, it would
be two components.

00:48:09.470 --> 00:48:11.500
You have A and B. The components
is the number of

00:48:11.500 --> 00:48:14.910
independent species that
you have, minus

00:48:14.910 --> 00:48:17.120
the number of phases.

00:48:17.120 --> 00:48:19.780
So here we have two phases, the
gas phase and the water

00:48:19.780 --> 00:48:24.800
phase, plus two.

00:48:24.800 --> 00:48:29.340
So for this example here, then
we would have two components,

00:48:29.340 --> 00:48:30.680
C equals two.

00:48:30.680 --> 00:48:33.480
Two phases liquid and gas.

00:48:33.480 --> 00:48:33.930
A and B are the components.

00:48:33.930 --> 00:48:34.950
And then plus two.

00:48:34.950 --> 00:48:40.220
So two minus two plus two,
F equals to two.

00:48:40.220 --> 00:48:45.400
Two degrees of freedom, two
independent variables.

00:48:45.400 --> 00:48:49.750
If I'm looking at this diagram
here, in this diagram here I

00:48:49.750 --> 00:48:52.210
have C equals one.

00:48:52.210 --> 00:48:54.740
One component, right?

00:48:54.740 --> 00:48:59.560
If I'm sitting where there's
only one phase, say, the

00:48:59.560 --> 00:49:04.930
liquid phase or the gas phase,
then p equals one.

00:49:04.930 --> 00:49:08.190
Then F is one minus one plus
two, is equal to two.

00:49:08.190 --> 00:49:09.620
Two degrees of freedom.

00:49:09.620 --> 00:49:11.800
And so in the pure phase,
I am in a plane.

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:14.610
The pressure and the temperature
are my two degrees

00:49:14.610 --> 00:49:15.190
of freedom.

00:49:15.190 --> 00:49:17.430
I can freely move around
the plane.

00:49:17.430 --> 00:49:20.370
At a coexistence line,
then the number of

00:49:20.370 --> 00:49:25.130
phases equals to two.

00:49:25.130 --> 00:49:30.540
Then I have one minus two is
minus one, plus two is one.

00:49:30.540 --> 00:49:33.350
The degrees of freedom is one.

00:49:33.350 --> 00:49:34.580
That's a line.

00:49:34.580 --> 00:49:35.520
I have one degree of freedom.

00:49:35.520 --> 00:49:38.750
I can move in the line, in
the line in a plane.

00:49:38.750 --> 00:49:41.130
Then if I change to the triple
point, where the number of

00:49:41.130 --> 00:49:45.510
phases is three, then the number
of degrees of freedom

00:49:45.510 --> 00:49:49.140
is one minus three is minus
two, two plus two is zero.

00:49:49.140 --> 00:49:50.950
I don't have any degrees
of freedom, I'm

00:49:50.950 --> 00:49:54.230
stuck at one point.

00:49:54.230 --> 00:49:57.960
So this is an example of the
Gibbs phase rule, specific

00:49:57.960 --> 00:50:00.180
where C happens to
be equal to one.

00:50:00.180 --> 00:50:04.910
And then, this is a more
generalized example.

00:50:04.910 --> 00:50:08.350
So next time, then, what we'll
do is we'll start by deriving

00:50:08.350 --> 00:50:09.890
the Gibbs phase rule.

00:50:09.890 --> 00:50:11.220
Which is not so hard.

00:50:11.220 --> 00:50:14.010
And then start on our way to
the colligative properties.

